<br>
First and foremost I'd like to apologize to Farrnusno for not being there.  I had RL obligations and was not able to attend.  I don't know that me being there would have made that much of a difference, however...  who knows.<br>
<br>
When a new (or substitute) leader steps into someone's shoes, especially someone who's done as good a job as Azure has, there's always a &quot;getting to know you&quot; period of time - when raiders are getting used to how the new leader operates, and the new leader is getting a feel for how and when they need to do what.  That can be a painful period, and it is really up to the old veterans of many raids in the past to try and keep things running smoothly.  A few well chosen words from a known and respected name can usually calm a lot of people down.<br>
<br>
When I started leading, most of the regulars already knew me because I'd been admin on Lagdalen's raids previously... so I really didn't have that much problem with people second guessing me or giving me problems...  I also had the priceless support of the uncanny and unflappable Kellory, who was stepping in to lead planes at the same time.<br>
<br>
I generally brought along (up to) a single group of 53+ support people for buffing and giant clearing.  They were usually people I knew or had been on multiple raids with me in the past.  I also never brought more than a full group of 53+ support personnel.  Frankly, if a single group of 53+'ers isn't capable of handling the giant pulling/clearing and buffline duties... they are the wrong people or the wrong classes.<br>
<br>
That being said, I was always grateful to have those that did come along to help, and I always let them roll if they wanted to.<br>
<br>
But here are some guidelines for raid behavior, as I've learned them from my own and others raids (and from my own mistakes) in the past:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    As a leader:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Stand firm and don't take crap from anyone.  If someone questions your authority or your decisions openly... well, they obviously know enough to run the raid themselves, right?  They can bloody well sign their guild up on KGC on the rotations and do it themselves.  &lt;insert comment about a Paladin (gasp!) being main assist here&gt;<br>
People wanna come on YOUR raid, they play by YOUR rules.  Period.<br>
On the other hand... listen to your veterans.  Even after running countless raids, I still occasionally forgot things.  There is no point in having a good admin team if you don't listen to them.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    As a veteran raider:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Support the leader in every way you can... and if you see something seriously wrong, give them a tell and let them know your concerns are.  An actual quote from me (though not on a KCoG raid... heh): You told &lt;raid leader&gt;, &quot;Hey, uh... the lair spawns are still up... we might want to pull them out and kill them before we charge in after Vox...&quot;. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>
But whatever you do, never, ever, under any circumstances, question the raid leader on an open channel.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    As a first time or reletively new raider:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Trust your leader and the admin to know their jobs.  If you have never actually been there and done that, no matter how many message boards and strategy discussions you've read, you probably don't have much of a clue about what needs to happen.  So strap in, settle down, shut up, and do what you are told.  Anything else is just going to make the raid take longer, and make you look like an a**hole.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>
That sounds kind of harsh, but it's true.  Until you've actually coordinated pulling giants out of the lair with a dragon in it, or run a buff-line, or been in a leadership position and been getting so many tells that your text window is scrolling faster than a epic monks combat-spam... you really don't know what it takes.<br>
<br>
There is no experience in the game that is analogous enough to fully prepare you for the burden of leading 50-60 people from so many different guilds with so wide a variety of skill and experience levels as come on KCoG raids.  If you've actually been there, then you should know better than to make trouble any.  If you haven't been there, you have no background from which to make any judgements. <p><img src=http://www.chrometiger.com/~anubis/stuff/kommisig.gif border=0 height=200 width=400><br>
